<div id="review_38102940" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/38102940" />
    <a title="Megan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1301544-megan"><img alt="Megan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1552021376p2/1301544.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/38102940?book_show_action=true">Nov 18, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Megan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Megan" href="/user/show/1301544-megan">Megan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">fans of wally lamb, historical novels, and characters studies</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1301544-megan?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer38102940" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16301096955936635502">Wally Lamb creates characters who become real as they are revealed on the page. When thinking about the book between readings, it was like revisiting acquaintances I was getting to know intimately. There are twists and turns, history that is revealed and unraveled like the labyrinth that he alludes to in the novel.<br/><br/>It&apos;s a book that took ten years to write, and these pages contain those ten years. Not only is does it delve into the family history of the characters for the past century, it revisits</span>
  <span id="freeText16301096955936635502" style="display:none">Wally Lamb creates characters who become real as they are revealed on the page. When thinking about the book between readings, it was like revisiting acquaintances I was getting to know intimately. There are twists and turns, history that is revealed and unraveled like the labyrinth that he alludes to in the novel.<br /><br />It's a book that took ten years to write, and these pages contain those ten years. Not only is does it delve into the family history of the characters for the past century, it revisits the occurrences that have shaped the past decade of our country's history; in this way, just by reading, you also become a character. There are moments of repetition in the story--perhaps needed, in a book this long, and which jumps around this much, but a bit much for certain points. <br /><br />Overall, a moving and intriguing book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16301096955936635502" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


