<div id="review_30677052" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/30677052" />
    <a title="Ab" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1307950-ab"><img alt="Ab" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1245783161p2/1307950.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/30677052?book_show_action=true">Aug 20, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ab" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ab" href="/user/show/1307950-ab">Ab</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer30677052&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer30677052" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16181634553246056295">Okay, I don&apos;t pretend to be an author of any kind or an authority on novel-writing, but seriously, where was his editor on this one? It almost seems he got to breeze through this publication process because he&apos;s written two previously good novels or because he&apos;s well-known or something. <br/><br/>First off, the book is divided into two &quot;parts&quot;. It&apos;s more like two totally different books -- the first being more about real history, etc. than an actual work of fiction. In my opinion, the first &quot;part&quot; should </span>
  <span id="freeText16181634553246056295" style="display:none">Okay, I don't pretend to be an author of any kind or an authority on novel-writing, but seriously, where was his editor on this one? It almost seems he got to breeze through this publication process because he's written two previously good novels or because he's well-known or something. <br /><br />First off, the book is divided into two "parts". It's more like two totally different books -- the first being more about real history, etc. than an actual work of fiction. In my opinion, the first "part" should have been scrapped altogether. It's simply a response to Columbine and is full of actual journal excerpts from the two student gun-men, quotes from their "video", and just factual information about a time (which was important) but not a fictional novel. It drawls on way too long without any significant plot development or devotion to any single character. I kept reading to sort of see where it was all going, and turns out it simply ends and then "part 2" begins. Part 2 was alright, but the first entire "part" was unnecessary to the development and plot of the second part -- meaning the first part was entirely extraneous. <br /><br />Second, the continual shifting between story lines was incredibly maddening and nonsensical. We go from current time, to Caelum's childhood, to his aunt's childhood, to his great-grandmother's live in the 1800s, and so on. Lamb's books usually have complex plots and intertwined bits, but they've been relevant in the previous novels. This book had them wandering wild all over the book. We're made to read journal entries spanning entire chapters from a 19th century quaker woman who happens to be Caelum's great-grandmother, which would be fine if they weren't so BORING! I almost book the book down several times, finally just skimming through this muck to get to the next relevant plot point. The plot that does develop amongst the irrelevant stuff if interesting and has potential to be very good, but with the other stuff definitely detracts from the main plot. When I had to continuously read entire chapters from Janis's thesis essay ABOUT the great-grandmother I almost screamed, "WHY!!" I get that through this "essay" we learn about some significant plot points, but only towards the end of the entire thing, the rest being really boring and pointless. <br /><br />As a fan of Wally Lamb's previous novels, I was disappointed. I wanted to like this book, especially since it took him something like 9 years to write. But it reads more like a rough reflection of all the shit that's happened in our world than an actual relevant novel. Sorry Wally. Not your best stuff. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16181634553246056295" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


